  "prompt_text": "A company's revenue grew 20% per year for 5 years. If initial revenue was $1M, what is the final revenue and total revenue over the period?",
  "response_text": "To find the final revenue after 5 years of 20% annual growth starting from an initial revenue of $1M, we can use the formula for compound interest:\n\n\\[ \\text{Final Revenue} = \\text{Initial Revenue} \\times (1 + \\text{Growth Rate})^{\\text{Number of Years}} \\]\n\nGiven:\n- Initial Revenue = $1M\n- Growth Rate = 20% or 0.20\n- Number of Years = 5\n\nPlugging these values into the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{Final Revenue} = 1,000,000 \\times (1 + 0.20)^5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Final Revenue} = 1,000,000 \\times (1.20)^5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Final Revenue} = 1,000,000 \\times 2.48832 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Final Revenue} = 2,488,320 \\]\n\nSo, the final revenue after 5 years is $2,488,320.\n\nNext, to calculate the total revenue over the period, we need to sum up the revenue for each year. The revenue for each year can be calculated as follows:\n\n- Year 1: \\(1,000,000 \\times 1.20 = 1,200,000\\)\n- Year 2: \\(1,000,000 \\times (1.20)^2 = 1,440,000\\)\n- Year 3: \\(1,000,000 \\times (1.20)^3 = 1,728,000\\)\n- Year 4: \\(1,000,000 \\times (1.20)^4 = 2,073,600\\)\n- Year 5: \\(1,000,000 \\times (1.20)^5 = 2,488,320\\)\n\nSumming these values gives us the total revenue over the 5-year period:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total Revenue} = 1,200,000 + 1,440,000 + 1,728,000 + 2,073,600 + 2,488,320 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Revenue} = 8,930,920 \\]\n\nTherefore, the total revenue over the 5-year period is $8,930,920.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (",
